# Backend Python

## Types and models

- Every request/response model is a Pydantic `BaseModel` with explicit fields. No `dict[str, Any]` at boundaries.
- Every DB entity is a typed SQLAlchemy model. No raw SQL except in migrations.
- Run `mypy --strict` clean. `Any` requires a comment explaining why.

```python
class ReportPeriodResponse(BaseModel):
    month: str
    total_hires: int
    hubs: list[HubBreakdown]
```

## Auth and authz

- Use the `require_user` and `require_role(Role.ADMIN)` dependencies. Never roll your own check.
- Hub scoping lives in one place: `backend/app/authz/hub_scope.py`. Report aggregation consumes the filter from there and nowhere else.
- Never log the session cookie, OAuth tokens, or service account JSON.

## Logging

- Use the shared logger from `backend/app/logging.py`. One JSON line per event.
- Include `request_id` and `actor` (if known). Redact PII.
- Never use `print()`.

## Migrations

- Alembic migrations are forward-only. Do not edit a migration that has shipped.
- Every migration has a rollback path documented in the docstring even if we do not run it.
- Data migrations in separate files from schema migrations.

## Tests

- Unit tests for aggregation, column mapping, and authz live under `backend/tests/unit/`.
- Integration tests (Sheets client, auth flow, audit writes) live under `backend/tests/integration/`.
- Each new endpoint ships with at least one happy-path and one unauthorized-path test.
